To improve the function, we can perform a more sophisticated analysis to check for the layout of the text. We can look for patterns like tabular structures, repetitive sequences of data, or specific spacing.

Here's an updated function that uses a more advanced approach to detect tables and columns:

```javascript
function doesItContainTableOrColumns(inputText) {
  // Check for common table patterns
  const tableRegex = /\b([A-Za-z0-9\s-]+\|)+[A-Za-z0-9\s-]+\b/;
  const columnRegex = /\b[A-Za-z0-9\s-]+\|\s[A-Za-z0-9\s-]+\b/;

  // Check for specific table and column patterns
  const containsTable = tableRegex.test(inputText);
  const containsColumns = columnRegex.test(inputText);

  if (containsTable && containsColumns) {
    return "TABLE_AND_COLUMNS";
  } else if (containsTable) {
    return "TABLE";
  } else if (containsColumns) {
    return "COLUMNS";
  } else {
    return "NORMAL";
  }
}
```

This updated implementation uses regular expressions to specifically look for tabular structures and columns. The tableRegex looks for patterns of text separated by "|" (pipe) characters, and the columnRegex looks for patterns of text separated by a "| " (pipe and space) sequence.

With these improvements, the function should now correctly identify the input as "COLUMNS" instead of "TABLE".
